Exercise 3.8.1

  1. the graph likely does not plt all the points, can use position=jitter to see all data points
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(position="jitter")

  1. Amount and Factor control the degree of jittering in geom_jitter()
?jitter

  1. geom_jitter() can be used with scatterplots to alleviate overplotting by giving more separations to the points that are plotted in the same space. geom_count() is used to count number of points at each location and maps the count in various size of bubbles. geom_count might be more useful in large data sets since thescatterplot may already be too cluttered.

  2. The default position adjustment for geom_boxplot() is position = “dodge”.

ggplot(data=mpg)+
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(x=drv, y=hwy))

Exercise 3.9.1

  1. What does labs() modifies axis titles as well as plot titles and subtitles

  2. The plot of highway vs city miles per gallon shows there is a direct relationships between city and hwy mileage performance - higher hwy mileage corresponds with higher city mileage. coord_fixed() forces a specified ratio between the physical representation of data units on the axes. It is important for clarity of data reporesentation so that the output is not misinterpreted. In this case x and y have the same units so fixed scale will give the best potrayal of the relationship between the two. geom_abline() Adds reference lines; helpful for plot evaluation

Exercise 5.2.4

library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)
  1. Had an arrival delay of two or more hours
filter(flights, arr_delay>=2)

Flew to Houston (IAH or HOU)

filter(flights, dest=="IAH" | dest=="HOU")

Were operated by United, American, or Delta

filter(flights, carrier %in% c("UA", "AA", "DL"))

Departed in summer (July, August, and September)

filter(flights, month %in% c(7, 8, 9))

Arrived more than two hours late, but didn’t leave late

filter(flights, dep_delay<=0, arr_delay>120)

Were delayed by at least an hour, but made up over 30 minutes in flight

filter(flights, dep_delay>=60, (dep_delay-arr_delay)>30)

Departed between midnight and 6am (inclusive)

filter(flights, sched_dep_time>=0000, sched_dep_time<=0600)
  1. between() filters values within the specified range

Departed between midnight and 6am (inclusive)

filter(flights, between(sched_dep_time, 0000, 0600))
  1. 8,255 flights have a missing dep_time. Dep_delay, arr_time, arr_delay are slaso missing. These might be cancelled flights.
(missing_dep_time <- filter(flights, is.na(dep_time)))
count(missing_dep_time)
  1. Why is NA ^ 0 not missing? Any value to power if zero is equal to 1, including any unknown value Why is NA | TRUE not missing? This is an OR statement which returns TRUE if either of the terms is TRUE, which is correct in this situation Why is FALSE & NA not missing? & operator will return TRUE only if both terms are the same. In this case we do not know what NA terms are which is why FALSE is returned Can you figure out the general rule? (NA * 0 is a tricky counterexample!). If the operation does not care whether NA is an integer or not, the response will be not missing, It will be missing if the operation can be perfomed on specific variable type only
NA^0
[1] 1
NA|TRUE
[1] TRUE
FALSE & NA
[1] FALSE
